<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="250" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d250">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/392½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-10">
                                    <hi rend="italic">10 May, 1915</hi>
                                </date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: This needs no comment
                            now, since the whole suspicious business has lost for the time being its
                            critical character.</p>
                        <p>I think that Sir Edward Grey acted very well and very wisely in the
                            matter, and I believe that your personal message to Count Okuma will
                            have more than a temporary effect on his mind.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>